      "message": "@Viktar, see my comments in the previous patch set. I argue against using an attribute. In particular, since such an attribute would be purely presentational (expanded or data-expanded attributes has no meaning on \u003cA\u003e tags) it\u0027s better to encode this as a class (which browsers are faster at styling).\n\nHowever, instead of the \"expanded-true\" and the (not used) \"expanded-false\" classes: I\u0027d prefer a computed function like ...\n\n  class$\u003d\"path [[_computeFileLinkClass(file)]]\"\n\n... where the function can return either the classname \"expanded\" or an empty string ...\n\n  _computeFileLinkClass: function(file) {\n    return file.__expanded ? \u0027expanded\u0027 : \u0027\u0027;\n  },\n\nIn this case, the CSS is simpler and less ambiguous. If the anchor has the \"expanded\" class then it\u0027s expanded.\n\nCompare with the dual \"expanded-true\" and \"expanded-false\" classes, where we introduce two ambiguous states, namely ...\n* ... when the anchor has both classes, OR ...\n* ... when the anchor has neither class.",
